======================================================================
PART 2: GROWTH RATES (log base 2 of each sequence)
  Sequences that grow at the same rate have parallel log curves.
======================================================================

  Exponential growth rates (per step):
    Fibonacci: phi = 1.618034
    3-strand Pascal: 4^(1/3) = 1.587401
    Jacobsthal: 2 = 2.000000
    Powers of 2: 2 = 2.000000
    Central binomial: ~4/sqrt(pi*n) per step
    Catalan: ~4 per step
    max_H: ~n/e per step (super-exponential)
    Triangular: polynomial (n^2/2), not exponential

  ALIGNMENT GROUPS (sequences with similar growth):
    Group A (growth ~1.6): Fibonacci (1.618), 3-strand Pascal (1.587)
    Group B (growth ~2.0): Jacobsthal, 2^n
    Group C (growth ~4.0): Central binomial, Catalan
    Group D (super-exp): n!, max_H, Bell, 2^C(n,2)
    Group E (polynomial): Triangular, C(n,2)

======================================================================
PART 3: GROUP A — THE PHI vs 4^(1/3) NEAR-ALIGNMENT
  phi = 1.6180339887
  4^(1/3) = 1.5874010520
  Difference: 0.0306329368 (1.8932%)
======================================================================

  phi^3 = 4.236068 = 2 + sqrt(5)
  (4^(1/3))^3 = 4
  Ratio: phi^3 / 4 = 1.059017
  So every 3 steps, Fibonacci gains ~5.9% over Pascal.

  phi^6 = 17.944272
  4^2 = 16
  phi^6 / 16 = 1.121517
  Every 6 steps (one full period), Fibonacci gains ~12.2%.

  For n < 20, Fibonacci and 3-strand Pascal are within 2x of each other.
  This means in our 'tournament-relevant' range (n=3..11),
  these sequences are effectively ALIGNED.

======================================================================
PART 4: TRIANGULAR NUMBERS AND FIBONACCI
  T_n = n(n+1)/2 — polynomial growth
  F_n ~ phi^n — exponential growth
  BUT: specific values coincide!
======================================================================

  Values that are BOTH triangular and Fibonacci:
  [0, 1, 3, 21, 55]
    1 = T_1 = F_1
    1 = T_1 = F_2
    3 = T_2 = F_4
    21 = T_6 = F_8
    55 = T_10 = F_10

  TOURNAMENT CONNECTION:
  T_n = C(n+1, 2) = number of arcs in tournament on n+1 vertices
  F_n = #{independent sets of path P_n}
  When T_n = F_m: the arc count of a tournament equals a Fibonacci number!

  T_2 = 3 = F_4: 3 arcs (n=3 tournament)
  T_5 = 15 = F_... no, F_5=5, F_7=13, F_8=21. 15 is NOT Fibonacci.
  T_6 = 21 = F_8: 21 arcs (n=7 tournament!) and F_8 = 21
  T_9 = 45 = max_H(6)!
  T_10 = 55 = F_10: 55 arcs (n=11 tournament) and F_10 = 55

  *** STRIKING COINCIDENCES ***:
  T_6 = 21 = F_8 = FORBIDDEN H VALUE = |Phi+(A_6)|
  T_9 = 45 = max_H(6) = C(10,2)
  T_2 = 3 = F_4 = max_H(3) = H(3-cycle)
  T_4 = 10 = C(5,2) = arcs at n=5 = V(Petersen)

